 ],
 "text": "For most of its history, China wrote in a language that nobody actually spoke, and hadn't spoken for well over a thousand years. You'd speak one kind of Chinese, and write a completely different one. Until about a century ago, written Chinese was winyanwin, classical or literary, Chinese. It was based on the language of the ancient classics, from over two thousand years ago, and it basically froze there. Meanwhile, spoken Chinese kept evolving, century after century, so the written language and the spoken language drifted further and further apart, until they were effectively two different languages. You spoke everyday Chinese, baihua, plain speech, but to write, you had to use this ancient, compressed, classical form almost no one actually spoke. Linguists have a name for this, deglossia, one language for the street, another for the page, and it meant that being literate didn't just mean knowing the characters, it meant mastering a near dead language on top of your own, which made reading and writing brutally hard, and kept them locked to a small, scholarly elite. Everyday speech simply wasn't considered proper, to write down. Then, starting around 1917, a scholar named Hu Shi led a movement with a radical idea, write the way you actually speak, use the living, spoken language, baihua, as the written standard. It caught on fast, within about a decade, the vernacular had replaced classical Chinese in schools and newspapers, so for two thousand years, China wrote in a language the time had left behind, and it took a 20th century revolution just to let people write the way they talk. We take it for granted that we write our own language, for most of Chinese history, that wasn't even allowed. Want to actually start learning Chinese? Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io"
